The doctors union has filed a court application for their impending jail sentence to be suspended for an additional two weeks.Labour Relations court judge Hellen Wasilwa had given KMPDU bosses up to Thursday to end their strike or go to prison for one month. The doctors said this was a price they were willing to pay as the strike entered its 52nd day.Read: KMPDU team not the first to face jail termAlso read: Government fails to avert health workers' strikeBut through secretary general Ouma Oluga, the medics said on Thursday that they needed more time to fully comply with Wasilwa's directions.Talks have failed and Health Cabinet Secretary Cleopa Mailu threw in the towel, but the doctors said an amicable solution will have been reached by the end of the two weeksThey also want the court to order the Council of Governors and Mailu not to frustrate negotiations and promptly call and attend all meetings.[VIDEO] Doctors union officials ejected from Treasury meeting after rejecting Uhuru's offerKMPDU officials facing jail are Oluga, union chair Samuel Oroko, and deputy secretary general Chibanzi Mwachonda.Others are vice chair Titus Ondoro, treasurer Daisy Korir, assistant treasurer Evelyn Chege and Allan Ochanji.Doctors prayed for them at a meeting at the Railways club in Nairobi on Thursday, in anticipation of the jail term.The medics went on strike on December 5 seeking to have the government implement the contentious CBA.The agreement was to give them a 300 per cent pay rise; review working conditions, job structures and criteria for promotions; and address under-staffing of medical professionals in state hospitals.KMPDU took the CBA to court for registration last year, but justice Monica Mbaru ruled that the union had to negotiate a new one with the Health ministry, Salaries and Remuneration Commission and the counties.Counties now employ nearly 90 per cent of doctors but were not involved in the 2013 CBA.President Uhuru Kenyatta offered doctors a 40 per cent salary increase but the doctors turned down the offer on grounds that it was not in line with the CBA.Also read: Doctors begin 'longest strike in history' over 2013 CBA agreement